# Correctness Proof

Suppose the first position where we can improve the string is `i`.

To minimize the string lexicographically:

1. We must make position `i` as small as possible.
2. Among all smaller characters, choose the smallest one appearing later.
3. Ensure that character has no occurrence before `i`, otherwise earlier positions become larger.
4. Since lexicographic order depends on the earliest differing position, this choice is optimal.

Thus the algorithm always produces the lexicographically smallest string.

---

# Complexity Analysis

### Time Complexity

Building first occurrence array:

```text
O(n)
```

Checking at most 26 characters for each position:

```text
O(26 × n)
```

Constructing answer:

```text
O(n)
```

Overall:

> **Time Complexity = O(n)**

(26 is constant)

---

### Space Complexity

First occurrence array:

```text
26 elements
```

Output array:

```text
O(n)
```

Auxiliary space:

> **Space Complexity = O(1)**

